Methods

IMAGE of work flow-MC?

Survey data

Field data collection was carried out at the athletes training centres using physiotherapy beds for examination, an external light source (Daray LED x200 medical examination light), and disposable dental examination kits (2156 – dental examination Pack. Clonallon). A digital data collection (DDC) form including the dental charts and questionnaire data was created using the KoboToolbox (KBTB) platform (preview available: https://kf.kobotoolbox.org/#/forms/a9bpX9EogskyPLJFghQzTq). The DDC forms were completed using Apple iPads (Apple Inc., CA, USA) on KBTB. Athletes self-completed 24-hour dietary recalls (24HR) using a separate DDC tool- Foodbook24 (FB24). Participants performed one interviewer-guided 24HR on the day of dental examination. They were subsequently invited to complete 3 additional recalls. To pseudonymise participants’ datafiles unique ID key code values were generated and randomly assigned to participants by creating a Microsoft Excel file to link FB24 and KBTB datasets. Participant ID codes were assigned and manually transferred from the keycode file to the web form and consent form for each participant.

Annie: Details for dental indices and OH assessments here- ICDAS, BEWE etc probably focus on ICDAS mainly for this paper.

Two core datasets were created from KBTB (oral health examination, socio-demographic and dietary-health behavioural data) and FB24 (multiple 24HR). The raw csv files were imported into R for data processing pre-analysis.

EDA/descriptive overall for both-

All food groups were mapped to a ‘short group code name’ to facilitate analysis of food groups. Consumption statistics (mean, median, SD, maximum, minimum, sum) for all nutrients were computed and summarised by subject, meal and food group level. Descriptive summaries of all nutrients was carried out for all completed recalls. Analysis of the distinct recalls indicated no substantial difference in food consumption across different recall, thus all recall data was retained. (THIS IS PROBABLY FOR RESULTS/DISC, appendix for regression lines) The FB24 data set was transformed and saved as RDS file for further analysis.

Consumption descriptions

  • total_consumptions the total number of consumptions across all recalls
  • max_daily_consumptions the maximum number of consumptions in a single recall (i.e. one day) across all recalls
  • mean_intake the mean daily intake across the recalls that the food group is consumed. Note this a mean daily intake rather than a mean consumption intake. All consumptions in a day were summed and an average taken which only includes the days of consumption.
  • max_intake and min_intakeare the maximum and minimum daily intake
  • avg_intake the average intake which includes recalls when the food was not consumed.

total_consumptions = sum(consumption), max_daily_consumptions = max(consumption), mean_intake = mean(intake), max_intake = max(intake), min_intake = min(intake), recalls = n_distinct(Recall #), sum_intake = sum(intake), avg_intake = sum(intake) / max(Recall #), (see FBgrouping Rmd code and add this to APPEDIX)

The ICDAS data from KBTB was collapsed into counts. ICDAS score I data was collapsed to include codes that show previous carious experience (ICDAS scores 3,8,97) while ICDAS II data was collapsed into ‘caries’ (ICDAS scores 2-6) and ‘non-caries’(ICDAS scores 0-1). DEFINE COMBINED ICDAS SCORES here…..

Both KBTB and FB24 RDS files were joined and data prepared for cluster analysis. Two athletes were removed (Gymnast and Triathlete) as there was only one from each sport and one athlete had incomplete dietary data (?). Potentially cariogenic food groups were selected (dentalFoodGroups) and described as ‘cariogenic’ based on previously published literature (CITE PM etc-NB add to APPENDIX table in Grouping FB24 Rmd -food group/ dental analyis csv). All other food groups were collapsed into one group and described as ‘non-cariogenic’ and water intake was categorised separately. For this analysis, nutrients were limited to carbohydrate, sugars, starch and energy intake. Meal types were collapsed to ‘snack’ or ‘main meal’.

We consider only cariogenic and non-cariogenic for total consumptions Water is not counted

fbIntakeNutrients <- fbDentalIntakeLong |>
  group_by(User, MealShort, Nutrient, GroupCodeShortIsCariogenic) |>
  reframe(
    total_consumptions=sum(total_consumptions),
    sum_mean_intake=sum(mean_intake),
    avg_intake=sum(sum_intake)/max(recalls)
  )  |> filter(!is.na(MealShort)) |>
  pivot_wider(
    values_from = all_of(values_cols),
    names_from = c(MealShort, Nutrient, GroupCodeShortIsCariogenic),
    values_fill = 0
  ) |>
  mutate(
    total_consumptions = total_consumptions_MEAL_CHO_Cariogenic +
      total_consumptions_MEAL_CHO_NonCariogenic
  )

is.boolean.str <- function(x) {
  isBool <- FALSE
  if (is.character(x)) {
    if (length(unique(x)) == 2) {
      isBool <- TRUE
    }
  }
  
  isBool
}

to.01 <- function(x) {
  as.numeric(factor(x)) - 1
}

is.cost.val <- function(x){
  length(unique(x)) == 1
}
